	   <a name=103514828973696></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f103514828973696><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=12&mid=103514828973696>RE: Solo...</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=12&mid=103514828973696#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=73372><span id=Sage>Malaclypse</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>114 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sun, Oct 20th 5:30 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.70]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;   Welll... couple things. First off pets are gonna stop conning yellow to you pretty quick. Secondly, for early levels, yeah fire pets are good. The damage shield lets them kill fast hitting mobs quick, IF they survive. And that's the catch right there. Fire pets have the least hp out of the 4. And you're gonna start noticing that pretty soon. Mainly fire pets at higher levels (30+) are best used for clearing greeny trash, because you're going to end up having to dump heals on them almost constantly. And while fire pet damage shields are a little better than ours (I think), They're very situational.<br>     <br>     Now, earth comes in handy for soloing as they can take a lot of damage and rarely avoid a hit, which means any damage shield ya toss on em will almost always do damage. They get hit, but usually not for a lot. However their root becomes a problem in groups, because rather than run, a mob that's rooted keeps fighting and doing damage to your party.<br>     <br>     For grouping Air is pretty damn good. Stuns keep caster mobs from getting spells off and air pets hit hard and fast. Pre-54 I'd go with air in group situations. (and yea, you will be grouping.)<br>     Water pets are average, except they regen HP quickly, which can save you downtime. And after 54 they get backstab. Two 54+ mages + two water pets = a REALLY fast exp group. Get em on either side of a mob and watch the BS damage go nuts.<br>     <br>     Which pet to go with is very situational. But before ya get stuck on one type and one type only, play with the others a bit. Get to know when and how to use them.<br><br>     As for soloing, yeah we're pretty good at it. Masters tho... I dunno. Right now the classes are pretty well balanced, and as Kranken pointed out to me once a long time ago (I didn't believe him then, but I'm starting to see his point) there's not a whole lot we can do soloing wise that a necro couldn't. They just do it differently. You can't really say that we can out solo any other class, because anyone that knows how to play their class can do some pretty neat things solo.<br>     <br>     While it IS entirely possible to solo a mage from 1 to 60, the problem is that it becomes hard to get equip and cash. Soloing is great for exp, but you can't beat grouping for loot. At certain levels, (36 - 40 or so) you CAN outsolo medium sized groups. But once ya top 51 or so, you can solo and get a couple neat items, or you can group and get lots of chances at lots of neat items. There are also going to be levels where it's just easier to group and get exp.<br>     <br>     Mages solo by having their pet beat the snot out of a mob while we nuke and heal the pet.<br>     <br>     Necros solo by sending in a pet, fearing, dotting, and laying other nifty spells on a mob while the poor creature runs screaming like a lil girl.<br>     <br>     Druids and wizzies solo by running around cobalt scar with like 8 wurms on em and generally making a nusiance of themselves.<br>     <br>     Thing is, this all works on the same type of mobs. And at the end of the day, the mob is still just as dead no matter how ya killed it.<br>     <br>     That being said mages probably have the most direct form of soloing, IE: without having to cast a bunch of support spells, buffs, debuffs...<br><br>     But you can't really say which way is best. It's like comparing apples and oranges.<br><br>     However, mages do rock much at soloing, and not a day goes by that I don't thank my lucky stars that I chose one for my main.<br><br><br>Good luck to ya,<br><br>Faelawen Starfyre, the Mad Mage of Povar, 54th season, leader of Defiant Heroes, arch nemesis of the evil squirrel empire.<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Thu Oct 31 07:59:06 2002</em><br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
